  - Negatives relative to my tastes: the mixes are described as “dry” and built from tight layered guitars and synth hooks with minimal ambience and multi‑tracked/harmonized vocals. That leans toward a more produced, multi‑overdub radio polish which risks the “hyper‑dry” or over‑produced feel I explicitly dislike (stripping needed pop sheen and intimacy). The emphasis on minimal ambience and layered synths suggests less of the analogue, in‑the‑room warmth and tape‑lean immediacy I prize.
Why I chose Back in Black and rejected the singles compilation
- Back in Black aligns more closely with my core sonic priorities: analogue warmth, dynamics‑preserving mastering, taut low end and snappy rhythm section, and concise, riff‑driven sequencing. Its described in‑the‑moment attack and tape‑lean character preserve the transient snap and headroom I insist on, and the upfront, centered vocals sit close to the rhythm rather than being airbrushed or over‑polished. These attributes directly address both my top‑end and low‑end preferences and avoid the loudness/overprocessing and thick midrange I dislike.
- The singles compilation does satisfy my appetite for short, sing‑along, vocal‑forward songs and three‑part harmonies, but its “dry, centered midrange” and multi‑tracked, tightly layered radio production trend toward the produced, less‑analogue feel I try to avoid. The minimal ambience and synth/guitar layering suggest the very kind of studio gloss and overdubbing that can undermine the intimate, tape‑lean warmth and tactile bass/drum snap I prefer.
For those reasons, Back in Black is the better fit for my specified priorities in mix character, mastering approach, rhythm section feel and vocal presentation.

